00:35:48.633 --> 00:35:50.560
I heard of a story, our
neighbor company here,

00:35:50.560 --> 00:35:53.850
Intuit, someone asked for
a CD to be sent to them

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:56.690
and they sent it in a huge box
with all this plastic wrap.

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:59.220
So the guy made a
YouTube video of, like,

00:35:59.220 --> 00:36:01.090
titled, "Does Intuit
Hate the Environment?"

00:36:01.090 --> 00:36:02.804
and it got all these
hits and that caught

00:36:02.804 --> 00:36:04.722
the eye of the sustainability
person at Intuit

00:36:04.722 --> 00:36:06.680
and they changed their
whole packaging process.

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:08.930
Now they just send it in a
paper sleeve and that's it,

00:36:08.930 --> 00:36:11.260
and so it can work.

00:36:11.260 --> 00:36:13.310
That was my
experience with that.

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:15.680
BEA JOHNSON: I really
believe that when

00:36:15.680 --> 00:36:18.096
I started doing
waste-free living,

00:36:18.096 --> 00:36:20.220
my husband said, you know,
what you're doing really

00:36:20.220 --> 00:36:22.880
doesn't matter, it's really
the big corporations out there

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:23.760
that matter.

00:36:23.760 --> 00:36:25.090
And I said, I don't agree.

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:26.750
I believe that we
as the consumer

00:36:26.750 --> 00:36:30.190
are leading the manufacturing
world because the manufacturers

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:32.930
only make what we're
buying, so if we buy crap,

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:33.970
they'll make more crap.

00:36:33.970 --> 00:36:36.330
If we buy packaging,
they'll make more packaging.

00:36:36.330 --> 00:36:39.490
If we buy in bulk, then
we're supporting sustainable

00:36:39.490 --> 00:36:42.060
practices and we're
literally voting

00:36:42.060 --> 00:36:45.820
with our money for more bulk
alternatives to be out there.

00:36:45.820 --> 00:36:50.150
So I think it's important to
realize the power of our money,

00:36:50.150 --> 00:36:53.320
and every time we buy
something, it's a way to vote.

00:36:53.320 --> 00:36:57.920
And if we buy right, then we're
basically spending our money

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:02.461
or investing our money into
a more sustainable future.

00:37:02.461 --> 00:37:03.460
JEFF CARLONI: Thank you.

00:37:03.460 --> 00:37:05.168
Kind of shifting gears
here a little bit.

00:37:05.168 --> 00:37:07.335
Being that California's
in a drought,

00:37:07.335 --> 00:37:09.710
this goes to I guess any of
you that want to answer this,

00:37:09.710 --> 00:37:11.251
is there a direct
connection that you

00:37:11.251 --> 00:37:13.870
can make between reducing waste
and saving water and helping

00:37:13.870 --> 00:37:16.870
out with the drought?

00:37:16.870 --> 00:37:19.189
MICHAEL O'HEANEY: So there's
some very direct ways.

00:37:19.189 --> 00:37:20.730
We're working on a
campaign right now

00:37:20.730 --> 00:37:25.520
around water bottling
in California.

00:37:25.520 --> 00:37:28.310
Nestle Waters, which is the
world's largest distributor

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:31.790
of bottled water, we're
working on a campaign-- they're

00:37:31.790 --> 00:37:37.125
taking water from a spring,
their Arrowhead brand-- well,

00:37:37.125 --> 00:37:39.500
they say it's a spring; we
think it's ground water, which

00:37:39.500 --> 00:37:42.740
is actually an important
distinction-- but in the San

00:37:42.740 --> 00:37:44.840
Bernardino National Forest.

00:37:44.840 --> 00:37:49.190
And I was saying
earlier before I

00:37:49.190 --> 00:37:52.220
came in, I got an email from
the head of Nestle Waters North

00:37:52.220 --> 00:37:54.086
America apologizing
because we've

00:37:54.086 --> 00:37:56.210
been sort of going to town
the last couple of weeks

00:37:56.210 --> 00:37:58.350
on a quote.

00:37:58.350 --> 00:38:01.500
He during a radio
interview was asked

00:38:01.500 --> 00:38:04.760
if Californians
are asking everyone

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:07.420
to sacrifice and to
sort of take less water,

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:09.150
would you consider
taking less water?

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:12.080
And he said, no, as a matter
of fact, if I could take more,

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:13.480
I would.

00:38:13.480 --> 00:38:19.430
So that's a very direct
case, but water use

00:38:19.430 --> 00:38:21.150
really around
bottled water is not

00:38:21.150 --> 00:38:23.180
just the water that's
in it, but the water

00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:25.180
it takes to produce the
plastics, the water that

00:38:25.180 --> 00:38:28.750
takes-- the
manufacturing processes.

00:38:28.750 --> 00:38:32.130
Agriculture in California
is really where it's at.

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:36.190
But I think there are ways
in living a simpler life

00:38:36.190 --> 00:38:42.060
and reducing your overall impact
that you can have an impact.

00:38:42.060 --> 00:38:44.820
I'm floored at some
level by the fact

00:38:44.820 --> 00:38:47.430
that Californians
over the last year

00:38:47.430 --> 00:38:51.090
have reduced their household
water use by 30%, 40%.

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:53.810
When the governor called
and the water boards

00:38:53.810 --> 00:38:55.550
and local officials
called and said,

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:59.500
we need people to stop using
so much water, people did it.

00:38:59.500 --> 00:39:00.639
People responded.

00:39:00.639 --> 00:39:01.180
It's amazing.

00:39:01.180 --> 00:39:01.971
I live in Berkeley.

00:39:01.971 --> 00:39:04.080
It's amazing to
me to drive around

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:06.690
and the lawns are all brown.

00:39:06.690 --> 00:39:09.810
It blows my mind.

00:39:09.810 --> 00:39:14.850
So I think there's this
idea that living a simpler

00:39:14.850 --> 00:39:19.150
life, that not partaking
in some of these kinds

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:26.670
of ridiculous products is
somehow a fringe or a weird way

00:39:26.670 --> 00:39:31.110
to live or that I'm the only
one who thinks like this

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:33.440
and that no one else thinks
like this, when in truth, I

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:36.320
think most Americans
share a core set

00:39:36.320 --> 00:39:40.120
of environmental values and when
asked, when really challenged

00:39:40.120 --> 00:39:43.590
to step up, people do.

00:39:43.590 --> 00:39:45.970
BETTINA LIMACO: Just to
add to the recycling piece,

00:39:45.970 --> 00:39:49.510
I think a lot of people think
that when you throw something

00:39:49.510 --> 00:39:53.520
in blue bin, something
like only 20% of plastics

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:56.740
actually get upcycled
because there's barely

00:39:56.740 --> 00:40:00.390
any-- think about what
plastic can become.

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:02.970
It can only become,
like, bumpers

00:40:02.970 --> 00:40:06.710
that you see for parking
or plastic t-shirts.

00:40:06.710 --> 00:40:10.930
And the amount of water it
takes to produce something out

00:40:10.930 --> 00:40:18.400
of plastic and to upcycle
something is enormous,

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:21.330
and all it does is delay the
entrance into the landfill.

00:40:21.330 --> 00:40:23.130
So it eventually
all ends up there.

00:40:23.130 --> 00:40:25.530
So once you're tired of
that plastic t-shirt,

00:40:25.530 --> 00:40:28.430
once you're tried of
that plastic anything,

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:30.732
it ends up in the
landfill, as well.

00:40:30.732 --> 00:40:32.940
JEFF CARLONI: Yeah, that
was kind of my next question

00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:35.510
is that I think a lot of people,
especially here at Google,

00:40:35.510 --> 00:40:37.590
we have everything is
recyclable and compostable.

00:40:37.590 --> 00:40:39.070
There's very little
actual things

00:40:39.070 --> 00:40:41.260
that are procured by
Google that are actually

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:43.320
able "landfill waste,"
so I think people

00:40:43.320 --> 00:40:44.640
have kind of a misconception.

00:40:44.640 --> 00:40:46.680
That's fine, we can
consume as much of this

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:50.130
as we want because it's going
to keep coming back forever.

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:53.510
But to your point, I think it's
something like only 16% or 17%

00:40:53.510 --> 00:40:57.130
more efficient use of resources
than making a virgin product.

00:40:57.130 --> 00:40:59.310
So all the
transportation and labor

00:40:59.310 --> 00:41:02.020
and like all those
inputs you said still

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:04.550
have a great impact
on the environment.

00:41:04.550 --> 00:41:05.900
Yeah, that's a great point.

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:08.150
BEA JOHNSON: And also we've
been told by the marketers

00:41:08.150 --> 00:41:10.490
that buying packaging
or convenience

00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:12.490
products saves time.

00:41:12.490 --> 00:41:16.550
My lifestyle saves me way more
time than my old lifestyle

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:19.190
because, for example, today
I've adopted products that

00:41:19.190 --> 00:41:21.680
are unpackaged, but
they're also less toxic

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:23.190
and they're multi-functional.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:27.900
So for example, to wash
ourselves from like head

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:30.810
to toe, to wash our
hair, our face, our body,

00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:33.410
and also to shave, we
use one bar of soap

00:41:33.410 --> 00:41:37.030
that we buy loose from the
health food store unpackaged.

00:41:37.030 --> 00:41:39.130
It costs us $2 for that bar.

00:41:39.130 --> 00:41:42.107
That bar has eliminated
four other toxic products.

00:41:42.107 --> 00:41:44.440
I no longer have to go to the
store to buy those things.

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:46.500
I no longer have to
put them in my car,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:49.080
take them up 36
steps to my landing,

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:51.250
store them, and then
use them, but also

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:54.960
then take all the containers
back down to the curb,

00:41:54.960 --> 00:41:56.890
and then go to the
store to buy more.

00:41:56.890 --> 00:42:01.220
And that's one example,
and I have like 100 others.

00:42:01.220 --> 00:42:06.850
We no longer buy paper towels,
plastic wrap, aluminum foil,

00:42:06.850 --> 00:42:09.390
sandwich baggies,
freezer bags, trash bags.

00:42:09.390 --> 00:42:11.240
All that stuff are
things that I used

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:14.090
to spend my money on going
to the store and buying.

00:42:14.090 --> 00:42:17.389
It's actually once you realize
how much time-consuming it is

00:42:17.389 --> 00:42:19.430
and you eliminate it from
your life, you're like,

00:42:19.430 --> 00:42:22.370
damn, I'm never
going back to that.

00:42:22.370 --> 00:42:25.350
We've been, again, led to
think that it saves time,

00:42:25.350 --> 00:42:27.920
but it really doesn't.

00:42:27.920 --> 00:42:28.920
JEFF CARLONI: Thank you.

00:42:28.920 --> 00:42:30.640
This question's actually
for you, too, Bea.

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:32.900
I know you recently gave a
talk at Burning Man, right?

00:42:32.900 --> 00:42:33.816
BEA JOHNSON: Yes, two.

00:42:33.816 --> 00:42:34.890
Actually two.

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:37.526
JEFF CARLONI: So Burning
Man, for those of you--

00:42:37.526 --> 00:42:39.150
does everyone know
what Burning Man is?

00:42:39.150 --> 00:42:40.335
Do I have to explain that?

00:42:40.335 --> 00:42:42.460
OK, so Burning Man is a
festival out in the desert.

00:42:42.460 --> 00:42:45.210
Basically they have this
mantra, "Leave no trace."

00:42:45.210 --> 00:42:46.877
They go out there,
they build this city,

00:42:46.877 --> 00:42:48.459
and then when they
take the city down,

00:42:48.459 --> 00:42:50.690
there's not a single strand
of anything left behind.

00:42:50.690 --> 00:42:53.330
So being that you were there,
that was your first time there,

00:42:53.330 --> 00:42:53.830
right?

00:42:53.830 --> 00:42:55.430
BEA JOHNSON: Yeah,
I was a virgin.

00:42:55.430 --> 00:42:57.800
JEFF CARLONI: Yeah,
you were a virgin.

00:42:57.800 --> 00:43:00.030
How did that experience--
you were already

00:43:00.030 --> 00:43:02.880
a person of zero waste, so how
did that experience of leave

00:43:02.880 --> 00:43:06.730
no trace, radical self-reliance,
MOOP patrol, all that stuff,

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:09.270
how did that change
your perspective?

00:43:09.270 --> 00:43:12.010
BEA JOHNSON: So doing zero
waste there for me was easy

00:43:12.010 --> 00:43:15.080
because I already do
backpacking with no waste,

00:43:15.080 --> 00:43:19.520
I buy food in bulk--
that is, dehydrated,

00:43:19.520 --> 00:43:23.880
such as soup mixes and
lentil soup, pea soup, things

00:43:23.880 --> 00:43:28.180
like that, or oatmeal, that
we can then add with hot water

00:43:28.180 --> 00:43:30.450
and get a meal going.

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:36.540
And I also brought 20--
I refilled, I should say,

00:43:36.540 --> 00:43:39.420
20 glass bottles of lemonade.

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:41.900
They don't really like you
to bring glass at Burning Man

00:43:41.900 --> 00:43:44.020
because if you break it,
then it's really hard

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:45.370
to remove from the ground.

00:43:45.370 --> 00:43:49.250
But I kept it within my tent, so
I knew that if something broke,

00:43:49.250 --> 00:43:52.910
then I could sweep
it and take it home.

00:43:52.910 --> 00:44:01.560
But I really love the leave no
trace principle of Burning Man.

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:05.050
It's made me much more
aware of my impact.

00:44:05.050 --> 00:44:08.760
When you pack your tent, you're
supposed to really fine-comb

00:44:08.760 --> 00:44:10.990
your area and they
also, of course,

00:44:10.990 --> 00:44:14.200
encourage you to do the
common areas, which I did.

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:16.700
But when I
fine-combed my area, I

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:19.530
was just amazed
to see that I had

00:44:19.530 --> 00:44:25.340
brought in dog hair, pine
needles, and feathers.

00:44:25.340 --> 00:44:27.930
The dog hair and
the pine needles

00:44:27.930 --> 00:44:30.020
were from previous
camp trips that I

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:33.670
had taken with that tent.

00:44:33.670 --> 00:44:36.220
I didn't lose much of my
hair because it was literally

00:44:36.220 --> 00:44:39.370
stuck to my head between
the dust of the Playa

00:44:39.370 --> 00:44:41.740
and the oils of my head,
it was one big mess.

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:42.990
Nothing fell out of it.

00:44:42.990 --> 00:44:45.660
I only found a couple,
but also the feathers

00:44:45.660 --> 00:44:48.410
out of my down sleeping bag.

00:44:48.410 --> 00:44:50.400
I had never really
thought of those things.

00:44:50.400 --> 00:44:53.250
To me, they were insignificant
when I had camped before,

00:44:53.250 --> 00:44:56.060
but there in the Playa, they
just really seemed out of place

00:44:56.060 --> 00:44:58.280
and I really enjoyed
picking them up.

00:44:58.280 --> 00:45:01.730
It was almost a spiritual
thing, and it really

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:07.380
made me aware of my impact
and I felt definitely

00:45:07.380 --> 00:45:10.230
it was a definite step further
from the little picking I've

00:45:10.230 --> 00:45:11.660
done before.

00:45:11.660 --> 00:45:15.800
It made me feel more connected
also with my environment.

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:17.342
JEFF CARLONI: Great.

