00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:35.430
are seeing this huge zero
waste movement taking

00:46:35.430 --> 00:46:40.000
a lot of weight, and
I can't mention names,

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:43.410
but very large
manufacturers have

00:46:43.410 --> 00:46:46.610
contacted me to get my
input on the products

00:46:46.610 --> 00:46:49.680
that they have so that
they can make them better.

00:46:49.680 --> 00:46:52.020
But I also want to be able
to put products out there

00:46:52.020 --> 00:46:54.660
to attract the zero wasters.

00:46:54.660 --> 00:46:57.040
So whether it be
the jars that I use

00:46:57.040 --> 00:47:01.890
to purchase my wet food or
the cloth bags that I have,

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:06.980
or even just in the things
that we need in my home,

00:47:06.980 --> 00:47:08.890
I think it's really
exciting to see

00:47:08.890 --> 00:47:14.990
that this movement is growing
so much that these corporations

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:15.820
are noticing.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:17.800
And the zero waste
lifestyle is just

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:21.910
in line with plastic-free
living, with tiny living,

00:47:21.910 --> 00:47:23.410
with collaborative consumption.

00:47:23.410 --> 00:47:25.500
We're all talking
about the same thing,

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:31.600
and actually even I read
that GE even themselves

00:47:31.600 --> 00:47:34.390
have noticed the
interest for tiny living

00:47:34.390 --> 00:47:38.660
and they are looking to adapt
their products to tiny living

00:47:38.660 --> 00:47:42.100
so they can get then those
consumers for themselves.

00:47:42.100 --> 00:47:44.747
But I'm sure you
see it probably?

00:47:44.747 --> 00:47:46.580
MICHAEL O'HEANEY: There's
a ton of companies

00:47:46.580 --> 00:47:48.788
doing interesting stuff,
both sort of on the consumer

00:47:48.788 --> 00:47:50.830
side, the sort of
consumer-facing side, the way

00:47:50.830 --> 00:47:53.580
that they're actually
dealing with the impact

00:47:53.580 --> 00:47:54.950
of their products.

00:47:54.950 --> 00:47:57.210
So probably not
surprisingly, Patagonia

00:47:57.210 --> 00:48:00.297
is a real leader in this area.

00:48:00.297 --> 00:48:02.630
They launched a program I
think two years ago now, maybe

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:04.950
three years ago,
called Common Threads,

00:48:04.950 --> 00:48:08.370
which is basically they'll
take back their clothing

00:48:08.370 --> 00:48:11.750
and recycle the clothing.

00:48:11.750 --> 00:48:14.492
incredible repair business.

00:48:14.492 --> 00:48:16.200
If you go to Patagonia's
YouTube channel,

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:18.420
they have some great
videos that are

00:48:18.420 --> 00:48:21.220
these moving, incredible
videos about this guy who's

00:48:21.220 --> 00:48:25.460
had this anorak for the last
20 years and sent it back

00:48:25.460 --> 00:48:29.250
and Patagonia repairs
it and gives it

00:48:29.250 --> 00:48:31.760
another couple of years of
life, or that kind of thing.

00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:33.830
So in the
consumer-facing side, I

00:48:33.830 --> 00:48:35.850
think there are a
lot of companies

00:48:35.850 --> 00:48:39.980
doing interesting things around
repair, around take back.

00:48:39.980 --> 00:48:42.460
The electronics
industry has done

00:48:42.460 --> 00:48:46.760
an enormous amount in the last
10 years around take back.

00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:49.430
Still a long ways to go.

00:48:49.430 --> 00:48:53.380
There's interesting
folks like iFixit

00:48:53.380 --> 00:48:58.100
that is actually basically doing
repair manuals for electronics

00:48:58.100 --> 00:49:00.450
so that you can
crack open your phone

00:49:00.450 --> 00:49:03.440
or whatever it is and
figure out how to fix it

00:49:03.440 --> 00:49:06.000
instead of dumping it.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.860
So there's sort of a lot of
interesting consumer-facing

00:49:08.860 --> 00:49:09.630
stuff.

00:49:09.630 --> 00:49:11.800
There's great companies
who are figuring out

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:12.780
new ways to do things.

00:49:12.780 --> 00:49:16.080
So like the reason we
use carpet squares now

00:49:16.080 --> 00:49:19.860
is this guy, Ray Anderson,
who founded a company called

00:49:19.860 --> 00:49:23.220
Interface Carpet and he
figured out a less toxic way

00:49:23.220 --> 00:49:26.520
to create carpets, and we use
squares because then you only

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:28.759
have to replace a square
when it gets worn instead

00:49:28.759 --> 00:49:29.592
of the whole carpet.

00:49:33.420 --> 00:49:37.480
And then just in terms of
campus life for big companies,

00:49:37.480 --> 00:49:42.010
the fact that there is a
compost bin in this room to me

00:49:42.010 --> 00:49:43.680
is remarkable.

00:49:43.680 --> 00:49:46.790
Food waste is a huge
part of municipal waste,

00:49:46.790 --> 00:49:48.670
and not a lot of
folks are set up

00:49:48.670 --> 00:49:51.900
to actually do that kind
of waste collection,

00:49:51.900 --> 00:49:53.840
so I think that's
important, as well.

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:56.410
So I think companies
aren't doing

00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:58.227
as much as I'd like
them to do, but there

00:49:58.227 --> 00:50:00.060
are a lot of great
companies who are looking

00:50:00.060 --> 00:50:03.710
at how to create better
products for their consumers,

00:50:03.710 --> 00:50:06.920
how to create a better
life for their employees.

00:50:06.920 --> 00:50:09.565
We're working with-- again,
not a big surprise company--

00:50:09.565 --> 00:50:11.880
we're working with Ben
and Jerry's right now.

00:50:11.880 --> 00:50:16.490
All of their scoopers,
the scoop shop employees,

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:18.380
are taking an online
boot camp we have

00:50:18.380 --> 00:50:21.030
around community involvement.

00:50:21.030 --> 00:50:23.800
They put a sort of big emphasis
on their employees being

00:50:23.800 --> 00:50:27.460
engaged in their
communities, so they

00:50:27.460 --> 00:50:30.330
are trying to do that,
which one of the reasons

00:50:30.330 --> 00:50:32.400
I mention community,
community is

00:50:32.400 --> 00:50:34.140
kind of the antidote to stuff.

00:50:34.140 --> 00:50:38.950
So we were talking earlier--
stuff swaps, finding places,

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:40.540
building, sharing communities.

00:50:40.540 --> 00:50:42.676
Berkeley, we have a
tool-lending library

00:50:42.676 --> 00:50:44.050
that's part of
the public library

00:50:44.050 --> 00:50:46.480
system, which is incredible.

00:50:46.480 --> 00:50:51.610
I don't need all of
these things for myself.

00:50:51.610 --> 00:50:55.490
I rented a dolly,
like a hand cart.

00:50:55.490 --> 00:50:57.120
I only need that
maybe once a year.

00:50:57.120 --> 00:50:59.504
Why do I need my own,
and probably not everyone

00:50:59.504 --> 00:51:00.670
on my block needs their own.

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:03.870
I can go to the library with
my library card, get a dolly,

00:51:03.870 --> 00:51:06.990
I can get a jack hammer,
I can get garden tools,

00:51:06.990 --> 00:51:08.810
you can get hammers
and screwdrivers

00:51:08.810 --> 00:51:11.790
and all the kinds of things
that you would possibly need.

00:51:11.790 --> 00:51:15.590
Instead of going to Home
Depot, I go to the library.

00:51:15.590 --> 00:51:17.020
So communities,
businesses are all

00:51:17.020 --> 00:51:19.120
doing super interesting
things, I think.

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:21.078
BEA JOHNSON: And there
is a lot to learn, also,

00:51:21.078 --> 00:51:23.190
from other countries.

00:51:23.190 --> 00:51:25.750
Last year when I
went to Brazil, I

00:51:25.750 --> 00:51:29.130
was invited to talk about
my lifestyle over there

00:51:29.130 --> 00:51:31.020
as the way of the future.

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:32.500
Interestingly
enough, I was given

00:51:32.500 --> 00:51:36.166
a tour of a grocery
that does zero waste.

00:51:36.166 --> 00:51:37.540
Now, when I entered
that store, I

00:51:37.540 --> 00:51:39.750
thought, oh, well, I can
do zero waste in that store

00:51:39.750 --> 00:51:41.920
because everything was packaged.

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:45.100
And I showed up
with my cloth bag

00:51:45.100 --> 00:51:48.500
and I asked if they would put a
pastry in my little cloth bag.

00:51:48.500 --> 00:51:51.220
And he said, well, because it's
you, they will, but otherwise,

00:51:51.220 --> 00:51:51.950
they wouldn't.

00:51:51.950 --> 00:51:54.240
And I'm like, OK,
well, that's a shame.

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:57.980
But on the other side,
in the back of the store,

00:51:57.980 --> 00:52:02.220
these guys used to
pay huge tipping fees

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:05.790
for logging all the packaging
from their supply chain

00:52:05.790 --> 00:52:10.360
to landfill, but they figure now
that those materials actually

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:13.190
could be a good
source of profit.

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:15.740
So they found a
way of separating

00:52:15.740 --> 00:52:19.770
all their different
materials and then were

00:52:19.770 --> 00:52:23.580
matched with recyclers that
then buy those materials.

00:52:23.580 --> 00:52:27.400
They even had a guy in that
grocery store whose job,

00:52:27.400 --> 00:52:30.910
the staff, whose job
it was to separate

00:52:30.910 --> 00:52:33.170
the food from the
packaging, the food

00:52:33.170 --> 00:52:36.660
that they were not able
to donate to a food bank.

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:39.140
His job was to separate
the food from the packaging

00:52:39.140 --> 00:52:42.340
so then they were able
to compost that food,

00:52:42.340 --> 00:52:45.340
and then they turned around and
they were selling the compost

00:52:45.340 --> 00:52:46.840
at the grocery store.

00:52:46.840 --> 00:52:50.930
So this was an
amazing example to me.

00:52:50.930 --> 00:52:54.750
Over there in Brazil where you
think, we're leading all this

00:52:54.750 --> 00:52:56.590
and we'll show the world.

00:52:56.590 --> 00:53:00.210
But no, there are amazing things
that are being done everywhere,

00:53:00.210 --> 00:53:04.690
and those guys realize
that now actually it

00:53:04.690 --> 00:53:07.460
saved them a bunch of money, but
they're also even making money

00:53:07.460 --> 00:53:09.702
from their waste material.

00:53:09.702 --> 00:53:11.160
MICHAEL O'HEANEY:
If you're looking

00:53:11.160 --> 00:53:14.440
